## Cross-linking conventions

The whole point of this audit is that the outputs form a **drillable knowledge base**, not 13 disconnected files. Follow these rules in every file you produce.

### Anchor slugs

Every addressable thing gets a stable kebab-case anchor in its canonical file, declared with Markdown heading IDs (`### Thing name {#slug}`). This keeps anchors stable even if headings are renamed.

| Thing        | Canonical file           | Slug format                         | Example                              |
| ------------ | ------------------------ | ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| Module       | `module-map.md`          | `module-{slug}`                     | `module-auth`                        |
| Endpoint     | `entry-points.md`        | `endpoint-{method}-{path-slug}`     | `endpoint-post-api-auth-login`       |
| Entity       | `data-models.md`         | `entity-{name}`                     | `entity-user`                        |
| UI widget    | `ui-surface-map.md`      | `widget-{page}-{name}`              | `widget-dashboard-revenue-card`      |
| Steel thread | `steel-threads.md`       | `thread-{slug}`                     | `thread-user-login`                  |
| Workflow     | `workflows.md`           | `workflow-{slug}`                   | `workflow-order-fulfillment`         |
| Job          | `background-jobs.md`     | `job-{slug}`                        | `job-nightly-reindex`                |
| Integration  | `integrations.md`        | `integration-{slug}`                | `integration-stripe`                 |

### Cross-references in prose

Whenever you mention a thing that has a canonical entry, link to it: `[User entity](./data-models.md#entity-user)` — never a bare name when a link is possible.

### Clickable Mermaid diagrams

Every Mermaid diagram that references addressable things uses the slug as the node ID and emits a `click` directive at the end linking to the canonical file+anchor. Example:

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  widget-login-form --> endpoint-post-auth-login --> module-auth --> entity-user
  click widget-login-form "./ui-surface-map.md#widget-login-form"
  click endpoint-post-auth-login "./entry-points.md#endpoint-post-auth-login"
  click module-auth "./module-map.md#module-auth"
  click entity-user "./data-models.md#entity-user"
```

Target: at least 80% of nodes in any diagram that reference addressable things must have a `click` directive. Nodes that are pure narrative labels (e.g., "User clicks", "Response returned") are exempt.

### Backlinks

Every artifact ends with a `## Backlinks` section listing what else points into it. Example in `data-models.md`, the `User` entity section lists every steel thread, workflow, and endpoint that reads or writes `User`. This is what makes the knowledge base navigable both ways.

## Large-repo handling

This skill is built for legacy codebases that can be thousands of files deep. Apply these rules when the target is large:

- **Sample, don't enumerate.** For any pass that would require reading every file (bootstrap, entry-trace), sample by directory — one or two representative files per folder — and only go deeper where signal warrants.
- **Checkpoint into `progress.md`.** After each command, write a short "what I found / what's left" block. If context runs out mid-pass, the next session picks up from `progress.md` + the current `docs/architecture/*.md`.
- **Trust the filesystem as state.** Never try to hold the whole map in working memory. Summarize into the architecture docs, then reload those summaries on the next pass — do not re-read the source to rebuild context you've already captured.
- **Stop and name the gap.** If a section of the repo is genuinely opaque (obfuscated, dead, or behind a binary), record it under `unknowns.md` with evidence, then move on. Don't fake confidence.

